    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-05-13T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-05-13T13:00:00-05:00" n="110"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d110">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">651.113/120a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France (<persName type="to">Straus</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-05-13T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 13, 1933—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>131. This morning’s <hi rend="italic">New York Times</hi> reports that France has
                    completed an agreement with the Italians<note n="1" xml:id="d110fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Journal Officiel de la République Française: Lois et
                            décrets</hi>, May 12, 1933, p. 4934.</note> similar to the Belgian
                        agreement<note n="2" xml:id="d110fn2">League of Nations Treaty Series, vol.
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">cxxxvii</hi>, p. 289.</note> which removes from
                    Italian products imported into France the French turnover tax. You will recall
                    that at the time of the Franco-Belgian agreement we made representations to the
                    effect that this discrimination should be rectified particularly in respect of
                    copper. American copper interests are again pressing the Department with regard
                    to this matter.</p>
                <p>You are requested to present a protest either orally or in writing, as you may
                    deem more appropriate, to the French Government, saying that this Government
                    cannot recognize this method of discrimination in favor <pb facs="0260" n="156"
                        xml:id="pg_156"/> of third countries on the excuse that such preferential
                    treatment arises out of an effort on the part of France to avoid double
                    taxation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
